You can install CloudSim on Windows for cloud resource allocation and scheduling experiments.

The easiest setup is:

Windows
Java JDK
Eclipse IDE
CloudSim package
Step 1 — Install Java JDK

Download and install Java JDK (Java 8 recommended for older CloudSim versions):

Recommended

Eclipse Temurin JDK 8

After installation, verify:

java -version

Example output:

java version "1.8.0_xxx"
Step 2 — Install Eclipse IDE

Download:

Eclipse IDE for Java Developers

Install and open Eclipse.

Step 3 — Download CloudSim

Download CloudSim:

CloudSim GitHub

Or older toolkit:

CloudSim Toolkit

Extract ZIP file.

Step 4 — Import CloudSim into Eclipse
Open Eclipse

Go to:

File → Import → Existing Projects into Workspace

Select extracted CloudSim folder.

Click:

Finish
Step 5 — Add Required Libraries

If libraries are missing:

Right click project:

Build Path → Configure Build Path

Add all .jar files from:

jars/
lib/
Step 6 — Run Example Program

Open example:

examples/org/cloudbus/cloudsim/examples/CloudSimExample1.java

Run:

Right Click → Run As → Java Application
Expected Output

You’ll see simulation logs like:

Starting CloudSimExample1...
Datacenter created
Broker created
VM created
Cloudlet executed
Simulation finished
Simple CloudSim Resource Allocation Example

Example VM allocation code:

int vmid = 0;
int mips = 1000;
long size = 10000;
int ram = 512;
long bw = 1000;
int pesNumber = 1;
String vmm = "Xen";

Vm vm = new Vm(vmid, brokerId, mips, pesNumber,
               ram, bw, size, vmm,
               new CloudletSchedulerTimeShared());

This creates a VM with:

CPU allocation
RAM allocation
Bandwidth allocation
